  <Fragment slot="headline">Tip Calculator Guide: How to Split a Bill Fairly</Fragment>

  <p>Splitting a restaurant bill sounds simple until tax, tip, shared dishes, and uneven orders enter the picture.</p>
  <p>A good tip calculator saves time and prevents awkward math at the table, especially when several people are paying.</p>

  <h2>Start With the Bill Total</h2>
  <p>Begin with the bill amount and decide whether you want to calculate the tip on the pre-tax or total amount. Many people choose the total for simplicity.</p>

  <h2>Choose the Tip Percentage</h2>
  <p>The right tip depends on the service level and local norms. What matters for the math is being clear before you split the total.</p>

  <h2>Add Tip to the Total</h2>
  <p>Once the tip amount is calculated, add it to the bill total to get the full amount owed.</p>

  <h2>Divide by the Number of People</h2>
  <p>If everyone is splitting evenly, divide the final total by the number of diners. That gives a quick equal split.</p>

  <h2>When Equal Splits Feel Unfair</h2>
  <p>If one person ordered much more than everyone else, an even split may not feel right. In that case, calculate each person's share first and then apply the tip proportionally.</p>

  <h2>Large Group Tip Problems</h2>
  <p>Large bills often create two mistakes: forgetting an automatic gratuity already added to the bill, or adding the tip twice by accident.</p>

  <h2>Best Tool to Use</h2>
  <p>Use the <a href="https://mycalcstool.com/en/tip-calculator"><strong>Tip Calculator</strong></a> to enter the bill, tip percentage, and number of people and get the total instantly.</p>

  <h2>Final Takeaway</h2>
  <p>The cleanest bill split is the one everyone understands. A tip calculator helps you avoid double counting, awkward rounding, and rushed table math.</p>
